"Meyer R., Joos F., Esser G., Heimann M., Hooss G., Kohlmaier G., Sauf W., Voss R., Wittenberg U.","The substitution of high-resolution terrestrial biosphere models and carbon sequestration in response to changing CO2 and climate",1999,"Global Biogeochemical Cycles","13","3",,"785","802",,,10.1029/1999GB900035,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033385509&partnerID=40&md5=a5d47570971f48e1ce09a10da3da6767","Physics Institute, University of Bern, Bern, Switzerland; Institute for Plant Ecology, Justus-Liebig-Universität, Giessen, Germany; Max-Planck-Inst. fuer Biogeochemie, Jena, Germany; Max-Planck-Inst. fuer Meteorologie, Hamburg, Germany; IPTC, J.W. Goethe Universität, Frankfurt am Main, Germany; Institute for Plant Ecology, Justus-Liebig-University, Heinrich-Buff-Ring 38, D-35397 Giessen, Germany; Max-Planck-Inst. fuer Biogeochemie, Tatzendpromenade 1a, D-07701 Jena, Germany; Max-Planck- Inst. fuer Meteorologie, Bundesstrasse 55, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Inst. fur Phys. und Theor. Chem., J.W. Goethe Universität, Marie Curie Strasse 11, 60439 Frankfurt am Main, Germany; Physics Institute, University of Bern, Sidlerstrasse 5, CH-3012 Bern, Switzerland","Meyer, R., Physics Institute, University of Bern, Bern, Switzerland, Physics Institute, University of Bern, Sidlerstrasse 5, CH-3012 Bern, Switzerland; Joos, F., Physics Institute, University of Bern, Bern, Switzerland, Physics Institute, University of Bern, Sidlerstrasse 5, CH-3012 Bern, Switzerland; Esser, G., Institute for Plant Ecology, Justus-Liebig-Universität, Giessen, Germany, Institute for Plant Ecology, Justus-Liebig-University, Heinrich-Buff-Ring 38, D-35397 Giessen, Germany; Heimann, M., Max-Planck-Inst. fuer Biogeochemie, Jena, Germany, Max-Planck-Inst. fuer Biogeochemie, Tatzendpromenade 1a, D-07701 Jena, Germany; Hooss, G., Max-Planck-Inst. fuer Meteorologie, Hamburg, Germany, Max-Planck- Inst. fuer Meteorologie, Bundesstrasse 55, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Kohlmaier, G., IPTC, J.W. Goethe Universität, Frankfurt am Main, Germany, Inst. fur Phys. und Theor. Chem., J.W. Goethe Universität, Marie Curie Strasse 11, 60439 Frankfurt am Main, Germany; Sauf, W., Max-Planck-Inst. fuer Meteorologie, Hamburg, Germany, Max-Planck- Inst. fuer Meteorologie, Bundesstrasse 55, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Voss, R., Max-Planck-Inst. fuer Meteorologie, Hamburg, Germany, Max-Planck- Inst. fuer Meteorologie, Bundesstrasse 55, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Wittenberg, U., Institute for Plant Ecology, Justus-Liebig-Universität, Giessen, Germany, Institute for Plant Ecology, Justus-Liebig-University, Heinrich-Buff-Ring 38, D-35397 Giessen, Germany","Strategies are developed to analyze and represent spatially resolved biosphere models for carbon sequestration in response to changes in atmospheric CO2 and climate by reduced-form, substitute models. We explore the High-Resolution Terrestrial Biosphere Model as implemented in the Community Terrestrial Biosphere Model (HRBM/CTBM), the Frankfurt Biosphere Model (FBM), and the box-type biosphere of the Bern model. Storage by CO2 fertilization is described by combining analytical representations of (1) net primary productivity (NPP) as a function of atmospheric CO2 and (2) a decay impulse response function to characterize the timescales of biospheric carbon turnover. Storage in response to global warming is investigated for the HRBM/CTBM. The relation between the evolution of radiative forcing and climate change is expressed by a combination of impulse response functions and empirical orthogonal functions extracted from results of the European Center/Hamburg (ECHAM3) coupled atmosphere-ocean general circulation model. A box-type, differential-analogue substitute model is developed to represent global carbon storage of the HRBM/CTBM in response to regional changes in Temperature, Precepitation and cloud cover. The substitute models represent the spatially resolved models accurately and cost-efficiently for carbon sequestration in response to changes in CO2 or in CO2 and climate and for simulations of the global isotopic signals. Deviations in carbon uptake simulated by the spatially resolved models and their substitutes are less than a few percent.",,"biogeochemical cycle; carbon cycle; carbon dioxide; carbon sequestration; climate change; climate modeling",,,,,,"Archer, D., Kheshgi, H., Maier-Reimer, E., Dynamics of fossil fuel CO2 neutralization by marine CaCO3 (1998) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 12, pp. 259-276; Bolin, B., Rodhe, H., A note on the concepts of age distribution and transit time in natural reservoirs (1973) Tellus, 25, pp. 58-62; Bolker, B.M., Pacala, S.W., Parton, W.J., Linear analysis of soil decomposition: Insights from the century model (1998) Ecol. Appl., 8, pp. 425-439; Bruno, M., Joos, F., Terrestrial carbon storage during the past 200 years: A Monte Carlo analysis of CO2 data from ice core and atmospheric measurements (1997) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 11, pp. 111-124; Cao, M., Woodward, F.I., Dynamic responses of terrestrial ecosystem carbon cycling on global climate change (1998) Nature, 393, pp. 249-251; Cramer, W., Kicklighter, D., Bondeau, A., Churkina, G., Nemry, B., Ruimy, A., Schloss, A., Comparing global models of terrestrial net primary productivity (npp): Overview and key results (1999) Global Change Biol., 5, pp. 1-15. , B. M. III; Emanuel, W.R., Killough, G.G., Post, W.M., Shugart, H.H., Modeling terrestrial ecosystems in the global carbon cycle with shifts in carbon storage capacity by land-use change (1984) Ecology, 65, pp. 970-983; Enting, I.G., Wigley, T.M.L., Heimann, M., Future emissions and concentrations of carbon dioxide: Key ocean/atmosphere/land analyses, Tech. Rep. 31 (1994) CSIRO, , Atmos. Res., Melbourne, Victoria; Esser, G., Sensitivity of global carbon pools and fluxes to human and potential climatic impacts (1987) Tellus, Ser. B, 39, pp. 245-260; Esser, G., Osnabrück biosphere model: Construction, structure, results (1991) Modern Ecology, Basic 